## 1. Incident‑Response Overview  

| Phase | Goal | Key Actions (cloud‑native) |
|-------|------|----------------------------|
| **Preparation** | Ensure you have an up‑to‑date run‑book, IAM‑controlled playbooks, and immutable logging. | • Enable **AWS CloudTrail** (or equivalent) across all regions, with logs sent to a dedicated S3 bucket that has **Object Lock** and **MFA‑Delete** enabled.<br>• Deploy a **Security‑Hub**/GuardDuty integration for continuous threat detection.<br>• Store run‑books in a version‑controlled repository (e.g., GitHub with signed commits). |
| **Detection** | Identify the breach quickly and with high fidelity. | • Review GuardDuty findings, VPC Flow Logs, and WAF logs for anomalous IPs, credential‑stuffing patterns, or unusual API calls.<br>• Correlate CloudTrail events with **AWS Config** rule violations (e.g., public S3 buckets, overly permissive IAM roles). |
| **Containment** | Stop the attacker’s foothold while preserving evidence. | • **Quarantine** the compromised compute resources (e.g., set the EC2 instance’s security group to deny all inbound traffic).<br>• Rotate **IAM access keys** and **session tokens** for any role that had access to the affected resources.<br>• If a container image is compromised, push a **new immutable image** to ECR and redeploy via the CDK pipeline. |
| **Eradication** | Remove malicious artifacts and close the root cause. | • Scan all storage (S3, EFS, RDS snapshots) with **Amazon Macie** and **Amazon Inspector** for known malware signatures.<br>• Re‑apply **least‑privilege IAM policies** (see § 3).<br>• Patch the application stack (OS, runtime, libraries) to the latest security‑fixed versions. |
| **Recovery** | Return to normal operation with hardened controls. | • Re‑enable traffic through a **WAF** with a strict rule set (SQLi/XSS, known bad‑user‑agents, rate‑limit).<br>• Enable **AWS Shield Advanced** (or equivalent DDoS protection).<br>• Conduct a **post‑mortem** and update the CDK code to codify the new security posture. |
| **Lessons‑Learned** | Institutionalise improvements. | • Add any newly discovered mis‑configurations to **AWS Config** custom rules.<br>• Update the **incident‑response run‑book** and train the ops team on the new procedures. |

